{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a43907ad-f5a2-4efb-83a9-f6896ab32fe6","content":"There are two complementary approaches — **inspect** the manifests, and **auto-install** exactly what's needed:\n\n### 1. Inspect workload manifests on disk\n\n```bash\n# Find your SDK path\nSDK_PATH=$(dotnet --list-sdks | tail -1 | sed 's/.* \\[\\(.*\\)\\]/\\1/')\n\n# The Android workload manifest declares exact pack versions:\ncat \"$SDK_PATH/../sdk-manifests/\"*/microsoft.net.sdk.android/WorkloadManifest.json\n```\n\nThat JSON lists every pack ID and version (e.g., `Microsoft.Android.Sdk`, platform-tools version, build-tools version, API level).\n\n### 2. Auto-resolve & install in CI (recommended)\n\nThe MAUI Android SDK ships an MSBuild target that programmatically resolves **and** installs the exact packages your SDK version requires:\n\n```bash\ndotnet build -t:InstallAndroidDependencies \\\n  -f net9.0-android \\\n  -p:AndroidSdkDirectory=\"$ANDROID_SDK_ROOT\" \\\n  -p:AcceptAndroidSDKLicenses=true\n```\n\nThis reads the workload's own dependency graph and calls `sdkmanager` for precisely the right `build-tools;X.Y.Z`, `platforms;android-XX`, and `platform-tools` — no guessing.\n\n### 3. Query without installing\n\nTo just **list** what would be installed (dry-run style):\n\n```bash\n# After 'dotnet workload install maui':\ndotnet build -t:ResolveAndroidDependencies -f net9.0-android -v:normal\n```\n\nThe resolved package list appears in the build output.\n\n**For CI**, approach #2 is the gold standard — it's self-updating as you change SDK versions and eliminates version drift entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d6d36977-8126-4e95-a22b-6dbcd73bdb4a","outputTokens":433,"requestId":"F3E1:256A51:1E69A10:2247699:69E81BBF"},"id":"9704fe68-74df-40bc-aba8-eb50ebe95f30","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:52:25.913Z","parentId":"1abf6b70-06e9-437c-9c9c-51b68fb310d0"}
